#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:1
msgid "Global allocators"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.28](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.28-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:5
msgid ""
"Allocators are the way that programs in Rust obtain memory from the system "
"at runtime. Previously, Rust did not allow changing the way memory is "
"obtained, which prevented some use cases. On some platforms, this meant "
"using jemalloc, on others, the system allocator, but there was no way for "
"users to control this key component. With 1.28.0, the `#[global_allocator]` "
"attribute is now stable, which allows Rust programs to set their allocator "
"to the system allocator, as well as define new allocators by implementing "
"the `GlobalAlloc` trait."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:14
msgid ""
"The default allocator for Rust programs on some platforms is jemalloc. The "
"standard library now provides a handle to the system allocator, which can be "
"used to switch to the system allocator when desired, by declaring a static "
"and marking it with the `#[global_allocator]` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:27
msgid "// This will allocate memory using the system allocator.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/global-allocators.md:32
msgid ""
"However, sometimes you want to define a custom allocator for a given "
"application domain. This is also relatively easy to do by implementing the "
"`GlobalAlloc` trait. You can read more about how to do this in [the "
"documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/alloc/trait.GlobalAlloc.html)."
msgstr ""
